{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20684"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77589"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"11786"},{"type":"tags","id":"12563"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32447"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic wounds are defined as wounds that fail to progress through the normal stages of healing. They represent a significant healthcare burden and can substantially impact patient quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological mechanism of venous leg ulcers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neuropathy with secondary bacterial infection","Peripheral atherosclerosis causing tissue ischaemia","Systemic metabolic abnormalities impairing healing","Prolonged compression of tissues against bone","Chronic venous hypertension leading to poor oxygen delivery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary pathophysiological mechanism of venous leg ulcers is \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic venous hypertension leading to poor oxygen delivery\u003C/strong\u003E. These ulcers develop most commonly in elderly individuals with conditions such as severe varicose veins or congestive heart failure that cause venous hypertension. Histologically, these wounds often show hemosiderin deposits (iron pigment) from red blood cell breakdown and chronic inflammation. The impaired healing is primarily due to inadequate oxygen delivery to the ulcer site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuropathy with secondary bacterial infection\u003C/strong\u003E is one component of diabetic ulcer pathophysiology, along with vascular disease and metabolic abnormalities. The neuropathy leads to decreased sensation and awareness of minor trauma.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral atherosclerosis causing tissue ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of arterial ulcers, particularly in patients with diabetes. The reduced blood flow leads to tissue atrophy and eventually necrosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic metabolic abnormalities impairing healing\u003C/strong\u003E is another factor in diabetic ulcers but is not the primary mechanism in venous leg ulcers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged compression of tissues against bone\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism responsible for pressure sores (also called decubitus ulcers or bedsores), which develop in immobilized patients when tissues are compressed between a bony prominence and an external surface.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distinct pathophysiological mechanisms of different chronic wounds is essential for appropriate management. Venous ulcers typically require interventions that address the underlying venous hypertension, such as compression therapy, while other types of chronic wounds require different approaches based on their specific pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic wounds fail to progress through normal stages of healing due to local or systemic factors that impair tissue repair.","Venous leg ulcers result from chronic venous hypertension and are characterized by hemosiderin deposits and poor oxygen delivery.","Arterial ulcers develop due to atherosclerosis causing tissue ischaemia, while diabetic ulcers result from a combination of vascular disease, neuropathy, and metabolic abnormalities.","Pressure sores form when prolonged compression causes local ischaemia and tissue necrosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 110"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T13:08:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T13:09:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13560"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94549"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","